Observation Details: Continuing bird from Lyster hide. Entered hide around 10.00 and quickly located the bird off to the right. Over next five minutes it pottered along the shoreline, picking at the vegetation and dodging the copious quantity of foam washing up on the shore, often dashing, occasionally pausing to probe, and gradually made its way up to and past the hide, then continued to the left until it went out of view, at its closest probably c. 40m so view was fairly decent.  Waited another 20 minutes for it to reappear but it didn’t so at that point I went in search of other things.  Resembled Common Sand but with conspicuous and extensive covert barring, plain edged tertials, yellowish legs and a relatively short tail so wing tips almost reached tail tip. No call heard. Didn't fly. Not seen to vigorously 'bob'/teeter as Common Sand frequently does.
Female performing "choking" courtship display.
in reproductive plumage

Brown upper body with spotted breast and belly.  It bobbed up and down and flicked tail pretty much constantly.  It was feeding along the grassy edge of the waterline beyond the water's edge where the beach should be but flooded and just to the right of the sanderling. It moved back to the water's edge by the parking lot pavement and kept moving to the right as it fed. It would take short flights further to the right as I approached.  Photos attached.

I would check on the nest each time I was there and this morning found 3 out of 4 eggs hatched. The adult was leading the chicks along the reed line to feed.The adult did go back to the nest to check on the last egg twice. Eventually the chicks were lead into the marsh, I expect they will remain there. The Killdeer did the same thing last month.

The nest was originally found by Carl Milanes  on May 24 2020  with only two eggs and he went back on May 29 2020 to find another two eggs for a total of four. Carl had contacted me to let me know about the nest and asked if I could get photos of the chicks when they hatched. We both had monitored this nest until the chicks had hatched. All four eggs hatched June 15 2020. Carl had witnessed the last two eggs hatch approx 6pm in the evening. It should be noted here Carl witnessed the adult fly off with an egg shell from the nest and dropped on the bank away from the nest. Carl and I were there on the June 16 to find all four chicks actively feeding on the bank of the pond. Carl had kept meticulous notes on this sighting so all details here are accurate  I had taken photos of the chicks and are included this report.

Observation Details: This is the first state record for this Atlas. Spotted breast, eye bar and bobbing tail, with three chicks. Another adult no too far away. I posted to local listserve and one of the best birders in the county came to see them, and confirm the ID. Earlier in the year there is a shallow pool of water about 100 yards by 30 yards with cattails on the back side. It dies up by the end of summer. This is near the corner of a large field that is not farmed. It is roughly 1/4 mile square. State forrest lands are on three sides of the field. I frequently see Killdeer, Song and Field Sparrows, Red-winged Blackbirds and one Am Kestrel here.

Observation Details: Counted as seen. They were at several ponds. There were six clustered together at the SW corner of the north large pond when I arrived. Easy to identify them as they fly away when you walk near them by the prolonged high-pitched calls and the white wing markings. Solitary Sandpipers do not call in as many notes and have dark wings without white covert markings (like all N.A. Tringa), but white tail borders.

Observation Details: Continuing from yesterday and the day before. One seen close on boat dock and the other was seen flying low over the water near the dam. At one point I actually laid on the ground and slowly inched my way across the raised sidewalk for about thirty minutes to within fifteen feet of the resting bird. I got a few pictures and video before the bird got spooked. I hadn't moved but I thought maybe he sensed me, so I was surprised when I stood up and a giant Garter Snake slithering past the spot where the bird had been. When he noticed me he immediately did a u-turn directly into the water and swam under the dock.

Observation Details: Juvenile feeding near adult, while adult stood watch. We saw the same pattern a couple of times along the river. One adult would stand watch in a prominent location like a rock or the top of a dry shoal, calling in a steady monotone way, and the fledgling(s) would forage nearby, at the edge of the grassy bank. The juveniles wouldn't stay in the open for long, and mostly foraged in the vegetated areas likely grass growing in currently dry parts of the river bed.
